{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_ilia_ver01/data/sn87055779/00271740475/1930021101/0216.xml":{"full_text":"STOCKS REMAIN WITHIN NARROW PRICE RANGE\n4\nTRADERS UNABLE\nTO START ACTION\nIN QUIET MARKET\nOnly Slight Gains Made\nDuring Mediocre Ses\nsion of Exchange.\nBy W. S. COUSINS\nL N. S. Financial Editor\nNEW YORK, Feb. 10.\u2014Both in the\nvolume of business and in the move\nments of stock prices, today\u2019s session\non the big board was a tame and un\nsettled affair as compared with the\nactive markets of last week.. Pro\nfessionals churned around the specu\nlative favorites within a narrow price\n9 range in an effort to \u201cstart some\nthing,\u201d but in most cases stocks\nwound up within hailing distance of\ntheir starting points.\nThe shorts in radio squirmed un\ncomfortably as that stock was up 2%\npoints to above 42 in heavy trading,\nbut the bears retaliated by crashing\nMontgomery Ward and Sears Roebuck\n2 to 3 points lower. Montgomery was\nsold on the disappointing sales record\nfor January. Sears Roebuck dropped\noff to 92 for a loss of 3%.\nAround noon the United States\nSteel corporation published its Janu\nary unfilled tonnage report, showing\nan increase of 51,500 tons in forward\nbusiness last month. Though this was\nsmaller than expected, it indicated a\ngood pick-up in steel trade in the first\nmonth of the new year, which was en\ncouraging for the bulls. Atlantic Re\nfining made an excellent showing in\nl its 1929 report, with $6.79 a share\nearned last year, of which nearly $2\naccrues to the last quarter of the\nyear.\nUnited States Steel ran into heavy\nselling from the start and dropped off\nto 181 but a number of the low\npriced favorites did better. Columbia\nGraphophone forged along to 3014\nfor a gain of 1% Yellow Truck sold\nabove 20 for the first time this year;\nGold Dust, Alleghany Corporation\ni and Commonwealth and Southern\nwere in the running for fractional\ngains.\ni\nI\nFinancial Digest\nBy Harris, Upham and Co.\nTREND IN BUSINESS CON\nTINUES UPWARD.\u2014By New York\nTimes.\nGeneral improvement shown in\nweek despite evidences of irregularity.\nSteel production gains. Automobile\nplants prepare for active year, sales\nalready on the increase. Commodity\nprices lower, credit conditions, how\never, are encouraging.\nFOR FIRST TIME lN NINE\nYEARS.\u2014By New York Evening Post.\nAccording to F. W. Dodge corpora\ntion, figures, increase was only two\nper cent, but January normally falls\nbehind December. January also had\nthe highest recorded volume of con\ntemplated new construction.\nMERGER OF DAIRY PRODUCTS\nAND KRAFT PHOENIX BEING\nCONSIDERED.\u2014By New York World.\nDeal still in formative stages.\nGAINS BY 46 CHAINS 9.53% FOR\nJANUARY.\u2014Says New York Times.\nSeems to concentrate more on\nprofits than on sales in 1930. I\nMACY SALES SHOW SUBSTAN\nTIAL GAIN.\u2014By New York Ameri-\ncan.\nDefinite figures not available until a\ncomplete audit is made.\nJ. C. PENNY SALES SHOW\nSHARP GAIN.\u2014By New York Amer\nican.\nIncrease 17.7% in January.\nWESTERN UNION SPLITUP EX\nPECTED.\u2014By New York Evening\nPost.\nFour or five for one exchange ex\npected. May inciease dividend from\n$8 to $10. Preliminary report for\n1929 showed earnings equal to $15.12\na share.\nCIGARET PRICE RISE DENIED.\n\u2014By New York Herald Tribune.\nAn official of the R. J. Reynold!\nTobacco Co. said no meeting of execu\ntives of tobacco companies had been\nheld to discuss the price situation.\nNEWS OF MARKETS IN PARIS\nAND BERLIN.\u2014By New York Times.\nFrench stocks fail to rally on vote\nof confidence in the government.\nTraders still hold aloof. Nearly all\nissues weaker on the German Boerse.\nLONDON SEES DECADE OF\nPROSPERITY IN THE UNITED\nSTATES.\u2014By New York Evening\nPost.\nBoom and slump viewed only as\nphases in America\u2019s progress, greater\nconsolidation in banking operations j\nhere predicted.\nBusiness Briefs\nBy HARRIS, PPHAM St CO.\nMotor Wheel Corporation declared\nqparterly dividend of 75c on common\npayable March 10, record February\n20. Three months ago a dividend of\n75c was paid.\nMUM\nI* New Jersey Zinc year ended Dec\nember 31 net profit $9,221,794 after\ncharges anr Federal taxes, against\n$7,443,545 in 1928. December quarter\nnet profit $2,276,188 against $1,998,617\nsame period 1928.\nmum\nTexas Railroad Commission issues\norder fixing pro-ration of oil output\nin Yates Field of Pecos County at\n100.000 barrels dally, reduction of\n30.000 barrels daily effective today.\na a n\nMiller Rubber Co, year ended Dec\nember 31st net loss $1,864,610 after\ndepreciation, inventory adjustments,\ninterest and other charges, against\nnet loss $3,434,901 in 1928.\nJewel Tea in year ended Dec. 28\nearned $6.04 a share on 280,000 com\n4 mon shares against $11.10 a share on\n120.000 shares in preceding year.\nTOLEDO PEED.\nTOLEDO, O., Feb. 10.\u2014Clover\u2014Import\ned cash old, $0; domestic: cash old, $10.75\nS; cash new. $11 S; February, $11 S;\nFebruary choice, $li 8; February choice\n$11.40 S; March $11.10 S: March choice,\n$11.50 8: alsike cash $10.05; February\n$10.65; March $10.80; timothy ca*U old,\n$3; cash new, $,1.25; March $3.40.\nCOTTON\u2019 MARKET.\nCHICAGO, Feb. 10.\u2014Cotton opened 0\nto 12 points higher today. 'March $15.13.\nup 8; May $15.41, up 6; July $15.00, up\n7; October $15.02, up 12.\n4\nNew York Stock Exchange\n'By THOMSON-McKINNON.\nA\nOpen High Low Clow\n16Vi 16 16V!\n33 31 32\nIT* 3\n27* *73\nAdr. Bom. 16\nAdv. Bom. Pfd. ..1\nAjax Bobber\nAllied Chemical ..275\nAlii* Chalmer* 69% 59Vi 68% 58V\nAlleghany.21% 82% 21% 32V\nAmerada Corpora. 20 20\nAmer. Agrl. Chemi. 6% 6\ni American Bosch 49 30% 49 60V\nj Amer. Brake Shoo 66% 60 801\nAmerican Can ....137% 138% 133% 137\nI Ame. Car and Fdy. 79% 79V\ni Amer. For. Fow. 95% 95? 93% 91V\nAmer. Home Prod. 58% 68% 58% 68V\nAmerican Loeomo. 99 99\nAmer. Lt. and Poor. 93 91% 91% 93V\nAmerican Badiator 36 36% 35%\nAmer. Steel Fdya. 49% 60 49% 49V\nAmerican Sugar 65% 64%\nAme. Tel. 